{
  "texts": [
    "Simple matrices, such as aqueous solutions or isolated compounds, tend to produce more consistent data that is easier to learn.",
    "However, complex matrices with multiple interacting ingredients, such as processed foods, fermented products, or multi-component dishes, often present significant challenges.",
    "These systems are more prone to nonlinear interactions, increased signal noise, and reduced reproducibility.",
    "As a result, they make sensory prediction more difficult and reduce model robustness.",
    "Addressing these limitations requires specialized model architectures that can capture high-dimensional, nonlinear relationships."
  ]
}